questions.question:
Consider the following proposal to the 'readers and writers problem.'

Shared variables and semaphores:
  aw, ar, rw, rr : integer;
  mutex, reading, writing : semaphore;

Initial values: ar = rr = aw = rw = 0
  reading_value = writing_value = 0
  mutex_value = 1

Process writer:
  repeat
    P(mutex);
    if rr > 0
      then begin
        aw := aw + 1;
        V(mutex);
        P(writing)
      end
    else begin
        rw := rw + 1;
        V(mutex);
        while (rr > 0) do skip
      end;
    critical section;
    P(mutex);
    rw := rw - 1;
    if aw > 0
      then begin
        aw := aw - 1;
        V(writing)
      end
    else
      while ar > 0 do begin
        ar := ar - 1;
        V(reading)
      end;
    V(mutex);
  until false;

Process granter:
  begin
    P(mutex);
    if aw = 0
      then begin
        rr := rr + 1;
        V(reading)
      end
    else
      ar := ar + 1;
    V(mutex);
    P(reading);
    other work
  end;

a. Give the value of the shared variables and the states of semaphores when 12 readers are reading and writers are writing.
b. Can a group of readers make waiting writers starve? Can writers starve readers?
c. Explain if the above solution is incorrect.

steps.apply:
The solution is INCORRECT. The critical flaw is in the writer process:

  rw := rw + 1;
  V(mutex);
  while (rr > 0) do skip;  // busy-wait WITHOUT holding mutex
  critical section;

After V(mutex), the writer releases the lock and then busy-waits on rr. However, between V(mutex) and checking rr, a reader can enter its critical section (rr is incremented by granter under mutex). So the writer may observe rr = 0 just as a reader increments rr outside the writer's view, and both proceed to their critical sections simultaneously.

This violates mutual exclusion: a writer and readers can be in their critical sections at the same time, which is the fundamental requirement of the readers-writers problem.

Conclusion: The solution is incorrect because the busy-wait on rr outside mutex does not guarantee mutual exclusion between readers and writers.
